<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-105-954  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 105 954.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Jan 29 1990 v7 n4 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dial 'outsources' to help make transition to MicroVAX 3800s.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, Glen.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Dial Corp signs a five-year, $10 million contract with AndersenConsulting for the outsourcing of its mainframe operations andtelecommunications network.andP;  The move is a temporary arrangementfor the duration of the company's system transition from its IBM3081 mainframe to DEC MicroVAX 3800 minicomputers.andP;  Dial has beendecentralizing operations and has warehouses and plantsnationwide.andP;  It has decided to abandon its IBM 3081 system becauseit is moving its data processing center and does not want toinvest in a new computer room.andP;  The DEC MicroVAX 3800s will beinstalled at headquarters and at still undetermined satellitelocations.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dial Corp. (contracts)Andersen Consulting (contracts).andO;Product:   DEC MicroVAX 3800 (Minicomputer) (business use).andO;Topic:     Data ProcessingCosmetic IndustryMainframe ComputersMinicomputersContractsTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Dial 'Outsources' To Help Make Transition to MicroVAX 3800sandM;PHOENIX, Ariz.andP;  -- Another major corporation has decided to downsize its dataprocessing platforms, and will &quot;outsource&quot; during the cutover from an IBMmainframe to DEC midrange systems.andP;  This temporary move puts a new spin on agrowing trend toward outsourcing.andM;Dial, which makes personal and household care products, including Dial soapand Brillo dish pads, has signed a five-year, $10 million contract withAndersen Consulting of Chicago to outsource its mainframe operations andtelecommunication network to Andersen.andP;  The transition is scheduled for May.andM;The deal, howeve, will not permanently eliminate Dial's internal dataprocessing department, as do most outsourcing agreements.andP;  More like atemporary heart transplant, Dial's outsourcing will be a bridge for thecompany's computer operations as it switches systems.andM;&quot;As they migrate to the VAX, usage of our IBM mainframe and, consequently,our fee will decrease,&quot; explained Jay Mohr, an Andersen partner.andM;Bill Tekien, Dial's director of information systems, said his company isdumping its IBM 3081 mainframe because the system is running at capacity anddoes not suit Dial, which has been decentralized and has warehouses andplants throughout the nation.andM;&quot;The 'central glass house' concept wasn't consistent with our style ofbusiness,&quot; Tekein said.andM;Instead, Dial will install MicroVAX 3800s at corporate headquarters andsystems at still undertermined satellite locations.andP;  Each Dial division willhave a hand in choosing its equipment and will pay for it from its ownbudget.andM;&quot;That way, they'll see what they're getting for their [information services]dollars,&quot; Tekien said.andP;  &quot;With mainframe you constantly have the feeling thatsomeone else is using something that you paid for.&quot;andM;Tekien said DEC mainframes offer better connectivity, programming andrelational database options than a replacement IBM mainframe would, but a keyreason Dial is dumping its 3081 is that it is moving its data processingcenter and does not want to invest in a new computer room.andM;&quot;We wee faced with a capital investment in a mainframe room at a time when wewere concluding that mainframes were not in our long-term plans,&quot; he said.andM;Under the terms of its contract, Dial will wean itself from its IBMmainframe.andP;  Andersen's data processing center in Dallas will assumeapplications such as payroll, accounting and order processing.andM;&quot;It will be transparent to the users,&quot; Andersen's Mohr said.andP;  &quot;When theyprocess a transaction, it will just process in Dallas instead of Phoenix.&quot;andM;Andersen will return operations to Dial as the company is able to handlethem, according to Mohr and Tekien.andM;Mohr said systems management is the fastest-growing segment within Andersen,generating almost $100 million in worldwide revenues last year.andP;  Companyofficials said they expect those revenues to reach $500 million by 1993.andO;</TEXT></DOC>